# Chapter 12: Connecting Everything Together

*In which we add memory, polish the rough edges, and call this thing done.*

---

## You Have a Working App. Now Make It Better.

The app from Chapters 10 and 11 works. A user can paste text and get quiz questions. That's real value.

But it's missing things that real apps have:
- **Follow-up questions** — the user wants to ask "can you explain what ATP is?" after seeing a question about it
- **Conversation memory** — the AI should remember the study text across a multi-turn conversation
- **Session history** — results shouldn't disappear on page refresh

This chapter adds those things. By the end, you have a complete, polished app.

---

## Adding a Chat / Q&A Feature

Users want to ask follow-up questions about the material they pasted. This is a natural conversational pattern — and exactly what LLMs are built for.

We'll add a second endpoint: `/api/chat`, which lets users ask questions about the text they pasted, with the full quiz context in memory.

### The Chat Endpoint

```javascript
// Add to src/routes/quiz.js

const CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `
You are StudyBuddy, a helpful AI tutor. You have been given a passage of study 
material and have already generated quiz questions for a student.

Your job now is to answer the student's follow-up questions about the material.

Rules:
- Only answer questions based on the provided study material
- If a question can't be answered from the material, say so clearly
- Give clear, educational explanations that help the student understand
- Be encouraging and supportive — learning is hard, and that's okay
`.trim();

quizRouter.post('/chat', async (req, res) => {
  const { studyText, conversationHistory, userMessage } = req.body;

  if (!studyText || !userMessage) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'studyText and userMessage are required.' });
  }

  // Build the messages array with full conversation history
  const messages = [
    {
      role: 'system',
      content: CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT
    },
    {
      role: 'user',
      content: `Here is the study material we are discussing:\n\n---\n${studyText}\n---`
    },
    {
      role: 'assistant',
      content: 'I have reviewed your study material and am ready to help you understand it. Ask me anything about it!'
    },
    // Include conversation history so the AI has context
    ...(conversationHistory || []),
    // The new user message
    {
      role: 'user',
      content: userMessage
    }
  ];

  try {
    const completion = await client.chat.completions.create({
      model: 'gpt-4o',
      messages,
      temperature: 0.5,
      max_tokens: 500,  // Keep answers focused and concise
    });

    const reply = completion.choices[0].message.content;

    return res.json({
      reply,
      tokensUsed: completion.usage.total_tokens,
    });

  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Chat error:', error);
    return res.status(500).json({ error: 'Chat failed. Please try again.' });
  }
});
```

---

### The Chat UI Component

```jsx
// frontend/src/components/ChatBox.jsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

const API_URL = 'http://localhost:3001/api';

function ChatBox({ studyText }) {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([
    { 
      role: 'assistant', 
      content: 'I\'ve read your study material! Ask me anything about it.' 
    }
  ]);
  const [input, setInput] = useState('');
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  const sendMessage = async () => {
    if (!input.trim() || loading) return;

    const userMessage = input.trim();
    setInput('');

    // Add user message immediately (optimistic UI)
    setMessages(prev => [...prev, { role: 'user', content: userMessage }]);
    setLoading(true);

    try {
      const response = await axios.post(`${API_URL}/chat`, {
        studyText,
        conversationHistory: messages,
        userMessage,
      });

      setMessages(prev => [...prev, { 
        role: 'assistant', 
        content: response.data.reply 
      }]);
    } catch (err) {
      setMessages(prev => [...prev, {
        role: 'assistant',
        content: 'Sorry, I had trouble answering that. Try again?',
        isError: true,
      }]);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  const handleKeyDown = (e) => {
    if (e.key === 'Enter' && !e.shiftKey) {
      e.preventDefault();
      sendMessage();
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="chat-box">
      <h3>Ask a Follow-Up Question</h3>

      <div className="chat-messages">
        {messages.map((msg, i) => (
          <div key={i} className={`chat-message ${msg.role} ${msg.isError ? 'error' : ''}`}>
            <span className="message-role">{msg.role === 'user' ? 'You' : 'StudyBuddy'}</span>
            <p>{msg.content}</p>
          </div>
        ))}

        {loading && (
          <div className="chat-message assistant loading">
            <span className="message-role">StudyBuddy</span>
            <p>Thinking...</p>
          </div>
        )}
      </div>

      <div className="chat-input">
        <textarea
          value={input}
          onChange={(e) => setInput(e.target.value)}
          onKeyDown={handleKeyDown}
          placeholder="Ask about anything in the text... (Enter to send)"
          rows={2}
          disabled={loading}
        />
        <button onClick={sendMessage} disabled={loading || !input.trim()}>
          Send
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

export default ChatBox;
```

Add `ChatBox` to the `QuizDisplay` component, passing in the original `studyText`:

```jsx
// In QuizDisplay.jsx, add at the bottom after the questions:
import ChatBox from './ChatBox';

// ... at the bottom of the return statement:
{submitted && <ChatBox studyText={studyText} />}
```

And pass `studyText` as a prop from `App.jsx` to `QuizDisplay`.

