## Rate Limiting: Protect Your API

Without rate limiting, a single user (or a bot) can spam your API endpoint and run up your OpenAI bill.

Add basic rate limiting to the backend:

```bash
npm install express-rate-limit
```

```javascript
// src/index.js — add before routes
import rateLimit from 'express-rate-limit';

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,  // 15 minutes
  max: 20,                    // Max 20 requests per IP per 15 minutes
  message: {
    error: 'Too many requests. Please wait a few minutes before trying again.'
  },
  standardHeaders: true,
});

// Apply to all API routes
app.use('/api', limiter);
```

This is basic protection. For production, you'd add user authentication and per-user limits.

---

## Input Sanitization

Users can input anything. Some of it is prompt injection attempts. Some of it is just weird characters that might break things. Clean inputs before passing them to the AI:

```javascript
// src/utils/sanitize.js
export function sanitizeInput(text) {
  return text
    .replace(/[\x00-\x08\x0B\x0C\x0E-\x1F\x7F]/g, '')  // Remove control characters
    .replace(/\s+/g, ' ')   // Normalize whitespace
    .trim()
    .slice(0, 8000);         // Hard length limit
}
```

Use it in your route handler:

```javascript
import { sanitizeInput } from '../utils/sanitize.js';

// In the route:
const cleanText = sanitizeInput(req.body.text);
```

---

## Environment Configuration

Your frontend is currently hard-coded to `http://localhost:3001`. That won't work in production. Fix this with an environment variable:

Create `frontend/.env`:
```
VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:3001/api
```

Create `frontend/.env.production`:
```
VITE_API_URL=https://your-production-api-url.com/api
```

Update API calls in the frontend:
```javascript
const API_URL = import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL || 'http://localhost:3001/api';
```

Vite automatically uses `.env.production` when you run `npm run build`.

---

## The Finished App: What You've Built

Step back. Here's what you have:

**Backend:**
- Express.js API server
- Quiz generation endpoint (AI-powered, with validation and error handling)
- Chat/Q&A endpoint (conversational AI with memory)
- Rate limiting
- Input sanitization
- Environment variable management

**Frontend:**
- React single-page application
- Text input with character counting and validation
- Quiz display with interactive answer selection
- Score calculation and explanations after submission
- Follow-up chat interface
- Session persistence
- Loading states, error states, empty states

**Architecture:**
- Clean separation between frontend and backend
- Environment-based configuration
- Structured JSON communication between layers

This is a complete, production-quality application architecture. Smaller than a commercial product, but using the same patterns.

> 🔨 **Try It Yourself**
> Do a full end-to-end test:
> 1. Paste a Wikipedia article section
> 2. Generate quiz questions
> 3. Take the quiz
> 4. Check your answers
> 5. Ask two follow-up questions via chat
> 6. Refresh the page — is your text still there?
>
> If all of that works, you're done. You built an AI app.

---

## Summary

- Conversation history is passed in the messages array — that's how AI remembers context
- Session storage persists UI state across page refreshes (not across devices)
- Rate limiting protects your API and your wallet
- Sanitize user input before sending to AI
- Environment variables separate dev and production configuration
- This architecture — React frontend + Express backend + AI API — scales to almost any app you'll want to build

